<subSubSection id="5CBC65591874FFE2FF35FE9148E8FDE9" pageId="3" pageNumber="489" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="141936D21874FFE2FF35FE9148E8FDE9" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,575]" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">
<emphasis id="26D2EAC01874FFE2FF35FE91490FFEC9" bold="true" box="[199,308,262,287]" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="70374B231874FFE2FEB7FE9149D0FEC9" author="Distant" box="[325,491,262,287]" pageId="3" pageNumber="489" refString="Distant, W. L. (1908) Rhynchota, vol. IV. Homoptera and Appendix (Pt). In: Bingham, C. T. (Ed.), The Fauna of British India including Ceylon and Burma, 501 pp. [Taylor and Francis, London.]" type="book" year="1908">Distant (1908)</bibRefCitation>
described this species based on unspecified number of specimens collected from “ 
<collectingCountry id="6CB176421874FFE2FF53FEBC48C9FE95" box="[161,242,299,323]" name="Myanmar" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">Burma</collectingCountry>
, Ruby Mines&quot; (presently Mogok). This species appears to vary in coloration with respect to the dark markings on the crown and the pronotum as already noted by 
<bibRefCitation id="70374B231874FFE2FC81FED94C26FEB1" author="Distant" box="[883,1053,334,359]" pageId="3" pageNumber="489" refString="Distant, W. L. (1908) Rhynchota, vol. IV. Homoptera and Appendix (Pt). In: Bingham, C. T. (Ed.), The Fauna of British India including Ceylon and Burma, 501 pp. [Taylor and Francis, London.]" type="book" year="1908">Distant (1908)</bibRefCitation>
. The male specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="6CB176421874FFE2FA90FED94DA7FEB1" box="[1378,1436,334,359]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">India</collectingCountry>
identified here have a fuscous stripe along the claval suture, costal margin and claval commissure, and the apical veins are fuscous and the forewings lack the golden yellow coloration of the female 
<typeStatus id="CB1D88701874FFE2FBBEFE0F4C47FE66" box="[1100,1148,408,432]" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">type</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="8C9D2A571874FFE2FB79FE014CCAFE79" box="[1163,1265,406,431]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 15" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1896,1919]" captionTargetBox="[208,1379,202,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[194,1391,195,1879]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 15. Habitus of species of Signoretia. 1 – 4. S. aureola Distant: 1 – 2. Type, female; 3 – 4, Male from Hunli; 5. S. benguetensis Baker, syntype; 6. S. bilineata Baker, syntype; 7. S. carinata Baker, syntype; 8 – 11. S. dulitensis sp. nov., holotype and paratype; 12 – 13. S. greeni Distant, holotype; 14 – 15. S. lunglei sp. nov., holotype. Figs 1, 3, 6 – 8, 10, 12, 14. Dorsal aspect; Figs 2, 4, 5, 9, 11, 13, 15, lateral aspect." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/167192/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
). However, the male genitalia are similar to those illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="70374B231874FFE2FD35FE2D4BB8FE05" author="Anufriev" box="[711,899,442,467]" pageId="3" pageNumber="489" refString="Anufriev, G. A. (1971) Study of leafhoppers from the tribe Signoretiini (Homoptera, Aunchenorrhyncha) with description of two new species of Signoretia Stal from western Africa. Bulletin de l'Akademie Plonoaise des Sciences, Serie des Sciences Biologiques, 19, 721 - 726." type="journal article" year="1971">Anufriev (1971)</bibRefCitation>
. This species can readily be recognised by the greatly elongated ventral process of the pygofer similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="D3A64D511874FFE2FC9DFE484C69FE21" authority="Baker" authorityName="Baker" box="[879,1106,478,503]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Signoretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="26D2EAC01874FFE2FC9DFE484BC9FE21" box="[879,1010,479,503]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">S. maculata</emphasis>
(Baker)
</taxonomicName>
. However, both species differ in the shape of the atrium of the aedeagus which is much narrower in 
<taxonomicName id="D3A64D511874FFE2FC53FD944C29FDCD" box="[929,1042,515,539]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Signoretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aureola">
<emphasis id="26D2EAC01874FFE2FC53FD944B94FDCC" box="[929,943,515,538]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="26D2EAC01874FFE2FC4EFD944C29FDCD" box="[956,1042,515,539]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">aureola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
compared to 
<taxonomicName id="D3A64D511874FFE2FB59FD944D14FDCD" box="[1195,1327,515,539]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Signoretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="26D2EAC01874FFE2FB59FD944C82FDCC" box="[1195,1209,515,538]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="26D2EAC01874FFE2FB35FD944D14FDCD" box="[1223,1327,515,539]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="489">maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in caudal view.
